chunks.translated_text:
The right [text] is Chapter Forty-Seven. {Yao Nai separates the three phrases on "good establishment" into a distinct chapter.}

One whose accumulated virtue is profound
is like an infant.
{Fu Yi renders it: "One whose accumulated virtue is profound is compared to an infant."}
Poisonous insects do not sting,
fierce beasts do not seize,
birds of prey do not strike.
{Fu Yi renders it: "Wasps and scorpions do not sting." Wang Bi renders it: "Wasps, scorpions, snakes, and scorpions do not sting."}
Bones weak and sinews soft, yet the grip is firm.
{For "grip," Ye Mengde renders it as [variant character].}
Not knowing the union of female and male, yet the [organ] stirs.
{For the blank character, Wang Bi renders it as "complete," Fu Yi as "turgid." This follows the Heshang Gong version.}
This is the perfection of essence.
Crying all day without hoarseness—
this is the perfection of harmony.
{Kong Anguo’s *Shiwen* renders it: "The voice does not grow hoarse," noting that "voice" should be "sigh." Fu Yi renders it: "Crying, the throat does not grow rough." Peng Si notes: *Zhuangzi* contains the phrase "the throat does not grow hoarse," so later scholars added the character for "throat." The *Yupian* cites the *Laozi* as "crying without wailing," while another version renders it "without becoming mute." Lu Xilong’s version omits the character "also" after both instances of "perfection."}

To know harmony is called constancy;
to know constancy is called clarity.
Indulging life is called ominous;
the mind directing qi is called force.
{Fu Yi renders "is called force" as "then is force."}
When things reach their prime, they age—
this is called not following the Dao.
{For "this is called," Wang Bi renders it "is called"; Fu Yi renders it "not the Dao."}
What does not follow the Dao comes to an early end.

{{Virtue that is constant does not depart;
returning to the state of infancy,
one’s accumulated virtue is profound.
Virtue is the power of softness, emptiness, and harmony.
Not stung, not seized, not struck—
this is one who preserves Heaven’s wholeness,
whom things do not harm.
"Firm grip" refers to the four fingers grasping the thumb.
The *Shiwen* notes: "The infant is yin."}}

Chapter Fifty-Three

The Dao is the profound mystery of the myriad things,
the treasure of the good,
the refuge of the not-good.
{Fu Yi adds *ye* after *Ao*; adds *suo* before *bao*. Gu Shenzi’s edition adds *bu* before *bao*.}

Fair words can be traded in the marketplace;
noble conduct can be exalted above others.
{The *Huainanzi* reads: “Fair words can be traded for honor; noble conduct can be exalted above others.” Fu Yi reads: “Honored words can be exalted above others.”}

If one enters into what is not good,
how can it be discarded?

Thus, when the Son of Heaven is established
and the Three Dukes are appointed,
though one may offer a large jade disk followed by a team of four horses,
it is not equal to sitting and presenting this Dao.
{Fu Yi reads: “presenting this Dao.”}

Why was this Dao so prized in ancient times?
{One edition omits *he*. Fu Yi reads: “Why was it so?”}

Is it not because one seeks and obtains it,
and with it, sins are remitted?
Therefore, it is prized by all under heaven.
{Chen Xianggu reads *bu yue* as *bu ri*. Wang Bi reads: “to seek and obtain.” One edition reads: “with it, sins can be remitted.”}

{This chapter speaks of the supreme value of the Dao, desiring that people know its worth and seek it. If noble conduct can be exalted above others, such that one attains the position of Son of Heaven or the Three Dukes, what could be more honored? If fair words can be traded in the marketplace, such that a hundred strings of cowries are bestowed, yet not equal to a single word of this Dao, what could be more precious? Why, then, did the ancients so honor and treasure this Dao? Is it not because it is the treasure of the good, and when sought, is obtained; the refuge of the not-good, and with it, sins are remitted? That it is the most prized under heaven is indeed fitting.}

Chapter Sixty-Four

Nothing in the world is more yielding than water,
{Yet in overcoming the hard and strong, none can surpass it.}
Nothing can take its place.
{As nothing can replace its efficacy.}
The soft overcomes the hard;
The weak overcomes the strong.
There is none in the world who does not know this,
Yet none can practice it.
{None know it yet none can put it into action.}
Therefore the sage declares:
{Thus the sage declares.}
One who can bear the disgrace of the state
Becomes the lord of the altars of soil and grain;
One who can bear the misfortune of the state
Becomes the king of all under heaven.
{One who bears the state’s disgrace
Is called the lord of the altars of soil and grain;
One who bears the state’s misfortune
Is called the king of all under heaven.}
Straightforward words seem paradoxical.
{The soft and weak overcome the hard and strong.}

